text: For yall newer people who sont know, Richard Roundtree starred as Shaft way back. This was the height of blaxploitation and Shaft cemented a lot of the halmarks of the genre. If yall watched the recent show Luke Cage youd notice a lot of the better non stereotyped elements of blaxploitation (like music, embracing a bit of corniness) were in it.  Now, Roundtree starred in three Shaft movies. The original is more so the cultural touchstone. In 2000 they actually remade Shaft starring the best man possible to play Shaft: Samuel L. Jackson. But notably this movie didnt “cancel” the continuity of the original Shaft as Jackson’s Shaft character was actually the nephew of OG Shaft and Roundtree even features in the 2000 Shaft movie.   So for those of you keeping track, this brand new 2019 Shaft movie has three generations of the family, original Shaft, second Shaft, and third kid Shaft. Which to me is hilarious as youve got the og Blaxploitation character, his “modern” more actionized version, and the third millenial version.

text: Dear friend, take comfort and joy in the fact that we can walk through each day knowing that "the LORD reigns forever!" For He lifts us up when we are bowed down.....An article in the Surgical Technology International journal says that looking down at a smart phone with your head bent forward is the equivalent of having a 60-pound weight on your neck. When we consider that millions of people around the world spend an average of 2-4 hours daily reading and texting, the resulting damage to neck and spine becomes a growing health concern.                                          It is also easy to become spiritually bowed down by the burdens of life. How often we find ourselves discouraged by the problems we face and the needs of those we love. The psalmist understood this weight of concern yet saw hope as he wrote about “the Maker of heaven and earth, the sea, and everything in them— who remains faithful forever. He upholds the cause of the oppressed and gives food to the hungry. The Lord sets prisoners free, the Lord gives sight to the blind, the Lord lifts up those who are bowed down, the Lord loves the righteous” (Ps. 146:6-8).                                        When we consider God’s care, His great power, and His loving heart, we can begin to look up and praise Him. We can walk through each day knowing that “the Lord reigns forever . . . for all generations” (v. 10). Look to Christ Jesus by first acknowledging that you are a sinner in need of our Savior. Welcome Yeshua (Jesus Christ) into your life. Receive grace through faith by believing in Jesus Christ and what He did on the cross, His death, burial and resurrection. You will then be sealed and justified in salvation. You will be blessed abundantly and your life will be forever changed! text: At first I was thinking "these geezers are too old for this shit" but once I saw them lined up as an intergenerational team I was totally sold on the idea. This is great. I won't be surprised if it's the best _Shaft_ movie ever (although honestly the bar is not that high). Looks cool and the writing doesn't look that bad. I really like the theme of the different generations of men in a family working together and mentoring one another. Looks like a cool and positive portrayal of masculinity and fatherhood. I almost said "black masculinity", but every race should be able to relate to this even though the characters are definitely black. Good stories have universal appeal, and so will this if they get the humanity of the characters right. I'm looking forward to this. I'd love to hear an old-school blaxploitation soundtrack, and not just modern music. Those groovy soundtracks were the best part of those movies. An intergenerational team of musicians inspired by the sound of the black bands of that era and their film scores (of course including Isaac Hayes) would really elevate this movie. They could totally get some great black musicians from the '70s that worked on the original movies to lead a band to create some old-school music, perhaps with a modern twist but not too much.
